			<a name="process_android"><h3>Process: Optimizing for Android</h3></a>
			<div class="indent-usability-header">
				<p>
					With an iOS app in development and ready to ship, the next focus was to optimize the app’s usability and interactions for Android. The following screens were redesigned with native Android interactions and Material Design principles.
				</p>

				<h4>Navigation</h4>
				<p>
					On every Android phone, a device navigation bar persists at the bottom with the Back, Home, and Overview controls. In designing the Glip Android app, we realized that placing an app navigation at the bottom would add another navigation very close to the system navigation, which could easily cause selection mishaps and would demonstrate an atypical layout for this OS.
				</p>
				<div class="text-center">
					<img src="/images/projects/glip-project/13-Device-Nav.png" class="image-top-bottom-margin">
				</div>
				<p>
					For a navigation that felt native on Android, we used a conventional navigation drawer that would swipe from the left. Since one could scroll up and down in a left drawer, this design would be scalable if we ever needed to expand the list of menu items.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

