			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-10 col-centered">
			<div class="indent-usability-header">
				<h4>Messages Screen Filters</h4>
				<p>
					On the Messages screen, we wanted to preserve the filters in order to provide users the ability to switch between different message views by sender. These filters would be helpful for those looking for direct 1-1 messages amongst an influx of team messages, for example.
				</p>
				<div class="text-center">
					<img src="/images/projects/glip-project/15-Filters-on-iOS.png" class="image-top-bottom-margin">
				</div>
				<p>
					We wanted to preserve the filters on the Messages screen since it would be helpful for those looking for direct 1-1 messages amongst an influx of team messages, for example. With testing however, users expressed that the iOS filter design looked like a main menu on Android.
				</p>
				<div class="text-center">
					<figure>
						<figcaption>TABS - EXPECTED BEHAVIOR ON ANDROID</figcaption>
						<img src="/images/projects/glip-project/17-Tabs-expected-behavior.png" class="image-top-bottom-margin">
					</figure>
				</div>
				<p>
					This was understandable, as sectional tabs on the top of an Android app typically served as the app’s primary navigation. Also, since we now moved the primary navigation out from the bottom of the screen, users would immediately see a row of filter icons upon arrival, and incorrectly identify as the primary navigation.
				</p>
				<div class="text-center image-bottom-margin">
					<figure>
						<figcaption>FILTERS ON ANDROID</figcaption>
						<img src="/images/projects/glip-project/18-filters-on-android.png">
					</figure>
				</div>
				<p>
					In order to avoid confusing the primary app navigation with the Message filters, we collapsed the filters into a dropdown. This design enabled users to understand the relationship of the filters to the Messages page, and also reduced the noise on the screen, allowing the messages to take center stage.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

